	(text "VBAT -> 5V Buck (1A)"
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 332.994 30.226 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 2.54 2.54)
				(thickness 0.508)
				(bold yes)
			)
		)
		(uuid "f71e5187-7629-419d-8b5c-659c8b13fcbf")
	)
	(text_box "There's always one of the 5V bucks in operation, unless there's power from USB. When external AUX voltage is applied, the V_AUX/VCC buck provides initial power to the system. Alternatively, if a battery is plugged in alone, the VBAT buck provides power to the logic.\nIn order to aid with a \"cold\" start, there's power from V_LEFT_AUX_IN and V_RIGHT_AUX_IN in addition to VCC. This diode setup makes it slightly less efficient, but this is fine.\n5V is stepped up to 12V for the high side gate drivers and potentially the fan. Since this also needs to work from USB 5V, a boost is needed.\nThere's also a 5V->VCC passthrough transistor to be able to use the USB's 5V power in a pinch, but this is quite slow. V_IN and V_OUT MOSFETs are locked off in this state.\nIf the 5V rail rises above 5.4V for some reason, ACOV is triggered and the main DCDC turns off automatically."
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 172.72 29.21 0)
		(size 69.85 36.83)
		(margins 0.9525 0.9525 0.9525 0.9525)
		(stroke
			(width 0)
			(type solid)
		)
		(fill
			(type none)
		)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 1.27 1.27)
			)
			(justify left top)
		)
		(uuid "5ad59111-8bb8-4833-b8e8-36e6076665c8")
	)
	(text_box "TODO: implement ACOV on 5V, to prevent operation when there's more than 5.4V on +5V, as this could indicate an unintended VCC->5V passthrough, which would damage devices"
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 16.51 162.56 0)
		(size 36.83 14.1714)
		(margins 0.9525 0.9525 0.9525 0.9525)
		(stroke
			(width 0)
			(type solid)
		)
		(fill
			(type none)
		)
		(effects
